AGI - Betsy Arakawa, Gene Hackman's wife whose body was found on the floor of the couple's house bathroom, probably died before her husband, said Dr. Heather Jarrell, chief medical investigator at the New Mexico Medical Investigator's office. Arakawa was last seen on February 11, when she was picked up by surveillance cameras while visiting a local CVS pharmacy and a dog food store before returning to her fenced community, said the sheriff of Santa Fe Adam Mendoza.
February 11 is also the last day Arakawa had communications via e-mail. According to Jarrell, her husband, Gene Hackman, probably died on February 18, when her pacemaker last recorded her heartbeat. "It is reasonable to conclude that Mrs Arakawa died first," Jarrell told reporters.
Gene Hackman also probably died of natural causes, said at the press conference Dr. Heather Jarrell. The 95-year-old was hypertensive, suffering from atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease and Alzheimer's disease, which according to Jarrell was "a significant contributory factor". &nbsp;
Dr. Heather Jarrell, head of medical investigator at the New Mexico Medical Investor's office, said that it is possible that actor Gene Hackman "did not know" about his wife's death several days earlier.&nbsp;Hackman "showed evidence of an advanced form of Alzheimer," he said.<br> A Hackman family spokesman had previously told CNN that Alzheimer's news "are totally false". To the question whether Hackman would be able to live alone and survive after the death of his wife, Betsy Arakawa, Jarrell replied: "I am not aware of what its normal daily functioning capacity was. He was in bad health. He was suffering from a serious heart disease and I think it eventually caused his death.
Hunger may have been the cause of the death of the dog found dead in a cage in the bathroom of Gene Hackman and his wife Betsy Arakawa last week, but the authorities are not sure yet. "I don't think we know the answer to this question," said the New Mexico State public health veterinarian, Erin Phipps, in response to a question at a press conference today in which he wondered whether the cause of dog death was hungry. "However, given the timeliness presented, it is a possibility."<br> Shortly after he answered another question, saying that dogs are unable to contract hantavirus lung syndrome, the disease that, according to New Mexico's head coroner, caused Arakawa's death.&nbsp;

